postcontent: Five 20 rounds boxes of Federal American Eagle Tactical Tracer Ammo 5.56x45This Federal American Eagle Ammunition is genuine Lake City Ammunition Plant overrun ammunition. This tracer ammunition is loaded to military specification and is perfect for providing the shooter with immediate feedback through trajectory visualization by allowing the bullet path to be seen. Tracer ammunition is a great choice for banging away at steel targets, casual plinking and high-volume blasting sessions. The military uses tracer ammunition as an efficient tool for signaling.  They are effective for use as pre-arranged signals between units and individuals; they also can be used to designate targets. As tracers burn very bright and very hot they may catch surrounding vegetation on fire, so they should only be used where there is a limited chance of the shooter starting a fire. This ammunition is loaded with a delayed ignition tracer meaning it will not ignite for 50-100 yards. This means the tracer is not burning up barrels prematurely causing damage to expensive firearms. This ammunition is new production, non-corrosive, in boxer-primed, reloadable Lake City brass cases. Local pickup at 37th N & Woodlawn

title: For Sale:  Side-by-side 1923 Belgian 12 ga shotgun
postcontent:
I have a 1923 Belgian 12 GA side by side shotgun for sale.  This gun has been in my family, it was my Grandfather's and is in excellent condition.  It has all standard provisional Liege, Belgium proofs.  It is a 12 gauge, made in 1923, ( in the pics... the hard to read cursive b designates 1923, and the 12 in a diamond is 12 gauge, pre-1924, as well as the other standard provisional proof marks and superior barrel marks, and inspector marks are all pre- 1924.   There are the three serial number stamps that all match showing it is original.
The shotgun is an "assisted opening" system and it has a three "bite" locking system.  The cocking system is hammerless, and automatically sets the firing pins when closed.  There is also a manual safety switch.  It also has ejector slides that assits to remove spent shells once the gun is opened after firing.  The maker mark, is on the underneath side of the barrells but is difficult to make out and I have not found anyone yet that can help me determine  the gun maker  (the maker symbol is marked with a crown and two capital letters).    You can also see that this gun was imported into New York state.  This is not a damascas barrell and this is able to be fired with modern  light loads.The engravings and woodwork are beautiful, and I have had appraisers look at the gun and I am pricing this gun well under those appraisals.  I am able to send much more detailed photos  of  the gun  and/or markings.  Serious inquiries only.  I have the gun priced to sell, and I'm not taking any low ball offers so please do not waste your time.I will sell the gun for $750 and I am not interested in trades, no low ballers please.  Again, if you are interested I can email better quality pics.Feel free to text or call me at 317-667-250fiveThanks David
